Yes, observing the behavior of other people in a social situation can provide clues to cultural norms and expectations.

For example, if you see someone skipping a group of photos from a ceremony, it can be assumed that this behavior is related to the cultural norms and expectations in that society. By observing this type of behavior, it can be discovered that it is acceptable in that culture.

Also, if you see someone speaking very quickly and clearly in a group discussion, it can be assumed that this behavior is related to the cultural norms and expectations in that public situation. By observing this type of behavior, it can be discovered that it is acceptable in that culture.

In short, observing the behavior of other people in a social situation can provide clues to cultural norms and expectations by capturing some motivational factors or objective demands.

Having access to individual behavior in the context of social situations and/or the social group should also be subconsciously combined with the general perception or sense of correctness or incorrectness among all members of the group. For example:

- Here he speaks without pause (speaking less) – this is a norm;
- Here she speaks very quickly (speaking more) – this is a deviation from the norm;
- Here he speaks much longer than the others – this is a norm;
- Here she does not pay attention to her surroundings (not looking at others) – this is a deviation from the norm;
- Here she avoids long dialogues (deviation from community) – this is a norm;
- Here he makes some gestures (mimicry) – this is a norm;
- Here she does nothing (no mimicry) – this is a deviation from the norm;
- Here he gestures towards his nose (open gesture) – this is a norm;
- Here she keeps her hands close to herself (restrained gesture) – this is a deviation from the norm.

